Bad-record handling — the mode option.

Real input data has bad rows. A field that should be a number contains text, a column is missing, a line is malformed. When a row does not conform to your schema, Spark needs a policy, and you set that policy with the mode option.

There are three modes. The default is permissive. In permissive mode Spark keeps the bad row but sets the failed columns to null. If you also name a corrupt-record column, it tucks the raw bad string into that column so you can inspect it later. Nothing is lost, but nothing stops your pipeline either.

The second is drop-malformed. As the name says, it silently drops any row that does not parse. Cleaner output, but the dropped rows vanish without a trace, so use it knowingly.

The third is fail-fast. It throws an exception on the very first bad row. This is the strict choice — you would rather the job stop loudly than carry suspect data forward.

One more production habit. Set a bad-records-path, and Spark writes the rejected rows to a separate location for offline inspection. You get clean data flowing through and a quarantine bin of everything that failed, ready to debug.
